ðŸ’» Technical Implementation
Basic Firewall Configuration
bash
# Block all traffic on port 31337
iptables -I INPUT -p tcp --dport 31337 -j DROP
iptables -I INPUT -p udp --dport 31337 -j DROP
Host-Based Access Control
bash
# Allow specific host, deny others
iptables -I INPUT 1 -p tcp -s 10.0.0.2 --dport 31337 -j ACCEPT
iptables -I INPUT 2 -p tcp -s 10.0.0.3 --dport 31337 -j DROP
Egress Traffic Control
bash
# Control outgoing connections
iptables -I OUTPUT 1 -p tcp -d 10.0.0.2 --dport 31337 -j ACCEPT
iptables -I OUTPUT 2 -p tcp --dport 31337 -j DROP

# Verify rule configuration
iptables -L OUTPUT -n --line-numbers
ðŸ” Security Insights
Rule order matters - iptables processes rules sequentially

INPUT vs OUTPUT chains control incoming vs outgoing traffic

Specific rules should precede general rules for proper filtering

Port-based blocking is fundamental for service security

Host-based filtering enables granular access control

Egress filtering prevents unauthorized outbound connections

ðŸŽ¯ Key Techniques Mastered
Firewall Rule Creation: Using iptables to create custom filtering rules

Rule Order Management: Understanding and manipulating rule precedence

Chain Selection: Choosing between INPUT, OUTPUT, and FORWARD chains

Traffic Specification: Filtering by protocol, port, source, and destination

Policy Verification: Testing and validating firewall configurations

Network Segmentation: Implementing security through network isolation

ðŸ“ Usage
